Higgs boson explored
The announcement of the likely discovery of the Higgs boson caused a valid stir last summer.
There is an opinion that this boson is involved in the mechanism that is responsible for all matter in the universe.
And it is also the last particle whose existence is predicted by the standard model - our best or "the least bad" explanation of the nature and behavior of matter - but which has not yet been empirically observed.
However, there is no one hundred percent certainty among the physicists that it is the Higgs boson.
There is no doubt that we have a completely new particle at our disposal, which closely resembles the Higgs boson, as predicted by the standard model.
The new data published this week during the Great Physical Congress in Kyoto confirms it, but there is still no data to be absolutely sure.
However, suppose it's the Higgs boson, as the risks of error appear to be small, and let's look at what it's all about.
In this world, there is a completely unquestionable law, according to which two things cannot occur at the same time in the same place.
This rule cannot be circumvented - and do not try too hard, otherwise you will hurt yourself.
Although particle physics is a very strange world, it turns out that a similar law applies to it: Pauli's exclusion principle, according to which two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time, if they are in the same "quantum state" - this "state" roughly creates some of their properties.
Furthermore, physicist particles are divided into two categories.
On the one hand, we find orderly citizens, or fermions, which obediently adhere to Pauli's principle.
And at the other end there are bosons, obsessed anarchists who value nothing at all - certainly not to this principle, which means that they can easily be in the same place at the same time.
These bosons are further divided into two groups according to the equipment (by the way, absolutely amazing), which is The Particle Adventure, in the Berkeley laboratories: mesons that we leave unnoticed here, and "strength particles" through which great natural forces spread, and with which the Higgs boson is probably somehow related.
However, it must be said that these bosons are not as exotic animals as can be guessed.
If you read this article, it is thanks to a boson with an unusual banality: a photon, or a "light particle", which is a "carrier" of electromagnetic force.
When a particle with an electric charge accelerates or changes its direction, it "cancels" the electromagnetic field in this particular place, similar to a pebble thrown into a pond.
From this "excellent" creates an electromagnetic wave (light, infrared or ultraviolet radiation, etc.) and this wave is nothing more than a photon - and therefore one of the bosons, "carriers of force".
A more Stable Field
It's also with the Higgs boson, except that it's necessary to "speak" another field, the Higgs field, to make this boson appear.
This Higgs field is much, much more stable than the electromagnetic field; to its excitation, it is necessary to achieve very high energy values, similar to the frozen level of the pond, which only a large boulder ripens.
For this reason, it is necessary to use such a huge accelerator of the part as the accelerator in the CERN laboratory - a large hadron accelerator with accommodating beam is a circle with a circumference of 27 km! - in order to develop such energy.
Analogy with the electromagnetic field is once again useful for us to clarify the relationship between Higgs and matter.
Neither all particles nor all materials react with the electromagnetic field.
Some, for example, magnets, do, but others do not - a piece of paper, for example, will never hold on its own on the refrigerator.
And it is still true that all particles do not react with the Higgs field: the ones that do so have a certain mass, while others (such as a photon, let’s look at it) do not have it.
And Mrs. Nováková asks, what about all these researches, what will they "bring us"?
From a science point of view, it is a confirmation of the validity of the standard model (SM), which allows physicists to investigate any mismatch between observation and prediction of SM.
Moreover, many physicists literally want them to be found, because the slightest difference could open the space of "new physics" and close some gaps in the model.
It should be noted that the model still has huge flaws, does not bring any clarification of gravity (smooth!) or dark matter, which makes up approximately 80% of the cosmic matter (again, dusk!).
However, CERN has not yet found such a contradiction.
Responses
The responses of these researches in the daily lives of Mr. and Mrs. Novák are very difficult to predict, but the mistake would be to think that there will be none.
Behold: in the very early 60's, the pioneers of the laser in Bell's laboratories had no idea of a revolution that their work will provoke.
They assumed scientific use, but nothing else.
Physicist Willard Boyle - who worked at Bell Labs, where the laser was invented in 1960, and who created the first permanent laser beam (before-bearing beams were pulsed) in 1962, I already said it - the laser was initially considered such a "labric toy".
Just imagine...
In addition, application can also result from all the tools that surround the research.
For example, the same Willard Boyle created a small light sensor in 1969 during his work focused on optics.
This sensor, although Boyle did not plan to do so at first, now serves as the "eye" of all digital cameras in the world and earned him the 2009 Nobel Prize in Physics.
Of course, this does not mean that the activities around the LHC must necessarily change our lives, but it means that one really never knows...
