In the case of Bitcoin, all network nodes are depositories of current accounts books, controllers, money issuers and buyers and sellers.
How does this network work?
Each transaction between two users actually takes place between two electronic addresses by e-mail.
However, the user can choose a different address for each payment, thereby ensuring anonymity.
The information file related to this transaction is electronically signed by a double-key encryption system.
The network can thus verify the legitimacy of the transaction.
Thanks to the content of the file, it is also possible to ensure that the exchanged bitcoins exist in the public book of current accounts, which is distributed across the network.
The key phase is to write this new transaction in this book.
It is done by solving the mathematical task assigned to computers, the solver of which, a temporary central banker, will have the right to write this additional line.
This is a phase of cutting the file; i.e., the transformation of a huge file into a shorter and unique digital imprint.
Computers "take over" this new transaction and add a number to it, only then "cut" the whole.
The goal is to find a number that provides a specific imprint (a lot of zeros at the beginning).
Once this number is found, the other nodes can easily check its correctness.
The transaction is then inviolably displayed connected to the string of all other transactions; any modification would change the fingerprint.
If the user would like to pay twice with the same money in a row (within ten minutes) for fraud, the network confirms only one of the two transactions - the other will be abandoned, because each of them has a different fingerprint.
A computer that solves the challenge will win 50 bitcoins.
In order to avoid inflation, this reward is regularly divided into two, probably until the end of 2012.
The number of bitcoins in circulation is thus limited to 21 million, but they can be divided into a hundred million, so the margin space is...
The difficulty of the assigned task also increases with the increasing level of calculation.
