President Mohammed Morsi has embarked on another game of poker.
While Egypt remains the most divided in its history because of the proclamation of a constitution that temporarily grants it unlimited powers, it has decided to play vabank.
On Wednesday, he announced, regardless of the opinion of all others, that the Constituent Assembly would approve the final wording on the day.
Less than a week ago, the head of state granted this assembly another two months to complete the necessary work.
For almost two years, Egypt has been using a provisional text that has been supplemented many times, which weakens the constitutional stability of the country and leads to legal conjecture.
This new initiative has only further strengthened the country's ambivalence.
From the opposition's point of view, the president remains in his "autocratic delirium," he continues to "speak his word" and "twipes the law."
His supporters, however, assure that this is a means of contaminating with the constitutional and political crisis as quickly as possible and to speed up the transition process.
A referendum should be held in two weeks.
This is a very short period of time that will force the Brotherhood to withdraw from the intention to clarify the text to the Egyptians after the article.
For the president, it is also a way to regain national and democratic legitimacy, while the whole country is torn by protests.
As confirmed in an interview with the US weekly Time, Mohammed Morsi appears to be convinced that the Egyptians will vote in favour.
Especially since this hasty-organized vote puts the Egyptian people before the ultimatum: "Either you approve my text, or I will keep unlimited powers" that should otherwise end after the approval of the new constitution.
And in this special atmosphere, 85 deputies of the aforementioned Constituent Assembly with a large majority of Islamists approved the text yesterday.
Most of the liberals were absent in the vote.
In mid-Nophraine, not long before the constitution was announced, they banished the door, saying they did not have the opportunity to assert their views.
Human rights defenders, civil society or members of religious minorities have mimicked their move.
In order to achieve a quorum, 11 alternates were hastily replenished yesterday morning.
Some of them are very close to the Muslim Brotherhood.
It is not surprising that the articles of the Constitution were often voted unanimously.
Commentators further questioned that one of the few disputes revolved around... a prayer hour when some members of the committee were of the opinion that the hours in the meeting room were not properly adjusted.
The text, which was voted on last night, consists of 234 articles.
The subject matter of general attention, Article 2, ultimately remains the same as the 1971 version of the Constitution and stipulates that "Sharia's Unions are the main source of law".
Salafist parties, for which the introduction of Islamic law is one of the fundamental requirements, hoped to replace the term "principles" with the term "rules," which would allow for stricter application.
For Islamists, the fact that this article has not been corrected represents a sign of their goodwill and respect for other parts of Egyptian society.
"Phypocrite," argues liberals, who see only the rhetorical problem in this.
According to them, the Islamization of the Constitution takes place through other articles.
They shall focus in particular on Article 220, which entrusts the University of Al-Azhar to an advisory role, in particular for the control of conformity of Sharia law.
According to Egypt expert Sophie Pommier, this is disturbing because "persons called to express their expression are not elected and have no democratic legitimacy.
You can see the beginnings of theocracy.”
The fears of the liberals are even more stirred up by the fact that the next rector of the university should be less moderate than the current one.
"There has been no specific religious consequence for now.
