Most of the lawyers who worked on this text are not lumber, but university workers, many of them graduated in French schools," said Alexis Blouet, who is preparing a job on the constitutional transition in Egypt.
However, it agrees that "there may be contradictions regarding the interpretation of Article 220, because the terms used in it belong to the religious dictionary.
There is in particular a reference to "fiqh" [Islamic Legal Science].
And in the future, the question may arise as to what extent civil judges are competent to comment on it."
The text approved yesterday, in addition to religious pages, is highly criticized because of the extended powers it grants to the President of the Republic.
The Muslim Brotherhood insists there has been a significant reduction in the regime.
Another place of contention: powers conferred on the military.
In accordance with the wishes of the representatives of the army, the verification of the defense budget will not be carried out by parliament, but by the National Council of Defense.
Furthermore, there will be no banning proceedings with civilians in military courts, as requested by the human rights association.
