- Surely it cannot be considered a panacea - the question of privacy arises, because we do not always want to inform others in our surroundings about our activities and intentions.
In fact, all types of interaction with computers are good, but in their own environment.
For example, to control devices in public places, we had a project in which we thought about gestures, but not about swagger, just such scoops, short.
Gestures would not be taken by the camera of the device, but with a bracelet that would monitor the movements of bones and muscles.
It is still large, but theoretically it can be reduced to the size of a wristwatch.
In general, however, the future has a mixed type of control, for example, a gesture + voice.
- And how?
- How do you ask me, for example, to give you this can of lemonade?
You will say it and at the same time show it.
- I usually just talk.
- Oh, it's going to be very difficult to recognize.
So you want to get users to adapt to what a machine can or cannot at the moment?
- That's not necessary at all, but it's a rapprochement.
I think that in the near future we will have to work primarily on developing new types of sensors that can more accurately detect human responses.
These can be, for example, laser sensors that provide a fairly good deep resolution, this is very important.
- If you are talking about your work with Xbox Kinect sensors, what are your requirements for modern cameras?
Is there not enough resolution, depth or anything else today?
Basically, the current generation - that's what we can reflect on in our work on three-dimensional recognition.
Of course, it would be good to get 8 megapixels at a rate of 1000 f/s.
But it's not just the megapixels themselves, it's like nuts and depth.
At the current point of view, all current technologies are insufficient for us - this adds to the work of designers of algorithms.
So we have to keep in mind not only the resolution in the X and Y-axis, but also Z.
So also very important is the speed, the number of shots per second.
Human movement is quite dynamic, and the current data flows of 30 frames per second are frankly a little short, especially for gestures.
Stephen Betishes of our laboratory in Redmond made a touch sensor with an adjustable processing delay of 1 to 100 ms, while current, mass-produced sensors are closer to the second value (60-100 ms).
