There is one problem that critics often point out: there is no touch response!
Hands don't feel anything!
What answers do your group prepare for this challenge?
In my lectures, I often say that augmented reality is the seventh consecutive breakthrough in the interaction between man and machine.
I think the addition of tasmeral sensations could easily become the eighth breakthrough.
So far, one of the interesting tricks is used - the use of the other hand as a certain kind of substrate for imaging.
It records compression in an excellent way!
But there are also technologies that are really aimed at adding the palpability of these "images in the air" - for example, interference with several directional ultrasound beams at the defined point where the finger is located evokes a tasting sensation, but it is still very weak - as if you were blowing on your fingers.
There is also a wrist bracelet that affects the nerve endings in the fingers - also a promising direction.
- Have you tried to fool your brain?
To think he feels what he seems to feel at the moment when he sees something?
- That's a good idea, we haven't tried that yet.
Here there is another challenge that will be fought for for a long time - how to get a person who physically finds himself in a very cramped space to believe that he is walking through an open, practically infinite space - we are also working on the concept of cross-country trails (not at all, as in clubs), moving platforms and also huge balls.
If brain delusion becomes a goal, then work is still for many years.
This is what makes working on virtual reality so appealing to researchers - many things are in their very beginnings.
