Of course, in complete conclusion, that is, if we do everything succeed and the end of the world does not occur...
It will be sung by all performers at all three concerts at the same time.
The anthems suddenly also connect in a unique live broadcast on Czech Television.
Words about this song were written and the main role of Jesus in the clip is played by Tomáš Hanák, sings in it also Xindl X...
How did you get to work with them?
We also cooperate with other personalities of the Czech cultural scene, due to the fact that we organize a lot of benefit events and concerts...
We are trying to involve them intensively in these projects.
It turns out that most of them are interested and entertained by our cooperation with us.
What will the proceeds from the concerts against the end of the world go for?
The equipment of the Studeo barrier-free educational centre, which we have been implementing with the Tapolistic Association in Jedlička Institute for six years.
Under students of the schools of Jedlička’s institute, the lecturers regularly attend and devote themselves to them in activities that they enjoy and interest.
Students themselves do not have the means to go to the lecturers themselves, so we try to allow them this way.
As part of the completion of the Jedlička Institute, a separate building will be built in the future, to which we will move with this project.
Several musical groups and performers will perform at each concert.
How did you choose them?
We tried to put together a program that will appeal to all generations, including children.
For example, Chinaski, Support Lesbiens, Illustratosphere with Dan Bárta, The Tap Tap, Marián Bango and Jiří Suchý will perform in Prague.
Full details can be found at www.kpks.cz.
Are you planning any similar "bombastic events" in the future?
In May we will perform at the Prague Spring for the first time, so here we will certainly prepare an interesting program with interesting guests.
Next year we would also like to play at the Czech National House in New York, and personally, while we are in the USA, I would like to connect it with performances in Washington and Chicago.
Your foreign plans are not minimalist, you have already performed, for example, in Madrid, Brussels, London or Moscow.
The Tap Tap is a group made up of disabled people.
How do you handle these trips logistically and organizationally?
It's not as bad as it seems at first glance.
We have five members in an electric wheelchair, its trucks have to travel in the luggage compartment, then, of course, we carry a large amount of cargo and crates with tools...
However, so far it has always been done without problems, both CSA and British Airways have been well prepared for us that I was surprised many times.
Even in Moscow, from which we returned recently, it was without problems.
Thanks to trips abroad, you can compare how they differ in wheelchair access, public access to handicapped people and the like.
What have you encountered so far?
After Madrid, Luxembourg, London and other places where everything works better than in our country, we have just seen in Russia that everything is still in the very beginning in the east.
Compared to Prague, Moscow is very barrier-free, here it is still unusual for a person on an electric wheelchair to move alone in the city center.
It does not pay for such a self-evident as that you prefer wheelchair users in an elevator.
Fortunately, there are already civic associations that try to draw attention to the problems of people with disabilities.
And in what way do we still have to catch up with the more developed countries?
There are a lot of things that we're still in...
However, it is important to mention that the improvement and improvement of the situation is always dependent on the efforts of the people involved in this.
In both London and Madrid, it is quite common for people with heavy disabilities to move independently in public, they can go to the toilet, to the museum, anywhere...
However, it is not very common that a large number of people with disabilities actively participate in social life, in which we are a little ahead with The Tap Tap!
Respect for the public or wheelchair accessible is one thing, but only when we become important athletes, artists, actors, politicians or lawyers, things start to change for real.
So far, these are isolated cases of people who have a strong will.
The Tap Tap is currently very popular, but let's go back a few years ago, what made you start it in 1998?
I joined the Jedlička Institute as an educator, where I had many young people around me who were interested in doing something.
And since I am a musician myself, I play, among other things, on the saxophone, so I and my colleague established an interest music club.
Well, over time, as our presenter Láďa Angelovič says, it got a little out of hand (laughs).
But has the popularity come in recent years, or am I wrong?
It is true that it helped us when we started to connect with well-known singers and also actively work to promote the band.
We realized that a job that is not seen, in fact, it was as if it did not exist.
Thanks to contributions from the European Union, we can also afford quality lecturers, equipment and so on.
Was your goal to make it with The Tap Tap this high?
From the beginning, I felt the potential to do something differently.
Showbusiness is overflowing with things where one imitates the other.
It is in a way logical, everything new is received carefully and it takes a long time.
Things that are unique are very few, but I dare say that Tap Tap is one of them.
The first impression of a person who sees us for the first time is, of course, regret, that is natural...
But the regret is utterly useless, because people with disabilities are no suffering from all abandoned beings we have to regret.
These are people who can live a full life and develop, of course, provided they have the necessary resources to do so.
I say that if something happens to people with disabilities, it's not just a shift for them, it's for the whole society.
Did this success also help that you are a strict boss, as many people have marked you?
When we want to do quality work, we have to be uncompromising in many things and demand a certain discipline.
I think that’s perfectly normal.
Some people come to us with a romantic idea and with their heads in the clouds, and when they find out that they have to rehearse twice a week, go to the preparation and spend a lot of time on the road to concerts, the enthusiasm quickly leaves them.
But that’s how it works everywhere, in every group that wants to work and that wants to achieve something.
The Tap Tap has twenty members.
How many of them were at the beginnings of it in 1998?
Only one Láďa Angelovich.
We are an open group, people are leaving and coming, that cannot be prevented.
Whoever has the will and taste always has an open door with us
