Poland and Cosmos.
Last week, Poland was adopted as the 20th member of the European Space Agency as the second country from the countries of the former Eastern Bloc (after the Czech Republic, which became a full member of ESA on 12 November 2008).
Poland started close cooperation with ESA in 1994 and over the next years participated in a number of projects of the agency.
Poland’s journey to the cosmos has started much earlier.
Polish enthusiasts were engaged in the cosmos before the Second World War; but they did not always meet with understanding.
For example, I will commemorate the lecture A. Šternfeld in the Warsaw Astronomical Observatory, who on December 6, 1933, presented ideas from his pioneering work Entering the Cosmonautics.
Thoughts of a young engineer (b. 1905) left the listeners cold and years later Šternfeld recalled that only dr. Jan Gadomski was interested in his work.
In 1934, Šternfeld won the Robert Esnault-Peltere and André Louis Hirsch Award for joining the Cosmonautics in France.
The mentioned Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966) later became a great promoter of astronomy and cosmonautics.
In Polish journals, he published hundreds of articles and wrote a number of books devoted to these scientific disciplines.
Gadomski became a world-renowned promoter of astronautics, and his contribution was also appreciated that one of the craters on the far side of the moon was named by his name.
Already in 1925, a rail drainage was built in Poland, which was to be equipped with a rocket engine.
Unfortunately, the author of the proposal is not known and the details of the project are not known.
It is not even clear whether the rocket should have been used to start the dressage or to brake it.
Information about this dressage is known only from the period press.
From 1933, Polish artillery has begun to deal with missiles.
The research was provided by Komórka Techniki Uzbrojenia in cooperation with prof. Mieczyslaw Wolf and Prof. Gustaem Mokrzyckeigi.
It is clear from the preserved materials that the research has reached the stage of practical tests.
However, the arrival of the German troops was interrupted by the research.
In 1937, a design of a photoelectric fighter missile was created in the professional press, designed by engineer Rohoziński and the following year the work of Rakieta - the torpedo powietrzna and rakitobombom lotnicza by Leliwy-Krzywoblock.
Both projects were intended for the military use of missile engines.
Just before the war, the Temporary Scientific Advisory Committee (Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy) dedicated to all the projects of military use of missile technology, which he coordinated all the work.
The committee was founded in 1937, but after two years of activity, its activities ceased to start the war.
After the war in the Polish press, other works dedicated to the cosmonautics appear in Polish Astronautyczne (Polkkie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
For the first time, it is mentioned in the company in the November issue of the 1954 edition of the 1954 magazine, in which there are four more comprehensive articles devoted to astronautics.
In one of them, from prof. M. Subotowicze, is proposed to create a company that will deal with cosmonautics.
At that time, the projects of artificial satellites were already underway, and it was clear that space research was a perspective field.
Since the beginning of 1956, the Polish Astronautical Society (PTA) has been trying to enter the International Astronautical Federation (founded in 1951) and already in the autumn PTA became a full member.
And the following year, the first PTA chairman Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959) became the vice-chairman of the International Astronautical Federation.
He held this position until his death in 1959.
Since 1956, PTA has significantly contributed to the development of the highly successful meteorological rocket RM (Rakieta Meteorologiczna), which became the first Polish rocket to conduct scientific research.
The first type of RM-1 was completed in 1957 and the first launch occurred on 10. October 1958.
The rocket with an interval of 1800 meters was about 80 cm long and its weight was less than 5 kg.
Later, an improved version of the RM-1A was built, and in the summer of 1959, flight tests of the two-stage RM-2 rocket were launched in the Bledov Desert.
The rocket was 1.4 meters long and its weight was about 11.5 kg.
Another developmental type should have been capable of real scientific work - the RM-34 rocket was supposed to have an output of up to 14.5 km and its task was to monitor the high-altitude wind.
In 1962, however, further developments were suspended.
The meteor-1 rocket developed between 1962 and 1965.
The rocket was conceived as a two-stage, its total length was 510 cm and the starting weight was 32.5 kg.
Three types (marked Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C) were developed, which differed in the size of the space for scientific instruments.
In the Meteor-1A rocket, a space of 0.4 liters, Meteor-1B with a volume of 0.34 liters and Meteor-1C with a volume of 0.62 liters were available.
The maximum range for all three types was 37 km.
Between 1965 and 1968, the development of the Meteor-2 rocket, the first flight tests began in October 1970, taking place at the Aviation Institute.
The Meteor-2 rocket had a starting weight of 380 kg and was able to carry a payload weighing 10 kg to a height of around 60 km.
Subsequently, the Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 versions were built.
It is also worth mentioning Poland's entry into COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960 and the creation of the COSPAR National Committee two years later.
Poland also participated in the exploration of space on Soviet artificial satellites, and in 1978 Polish pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became the second intercosmonaute after Vladimir Remko.
The abolition of the Public Works Act is not a solution.
Last week, the Constitutional Court repealed the Public Works Act.
The resolution sparked a lively debate in public.
It will certainly be interesting to look at the issue from a broader perspective.
The liberal-oriented economic systems in the EU, as in a globalised world, are based on the principle of more, unregulated competition.
In its effect, this means that the individual economic departments, the national economic systems, stand in a permanent conflict between each other.
The reason is the principle of free trade and free, unrestricted movement of private capital, along with unbridled financial speculation.
Due to the considerable differences in the price of labor, (mens) there is a price tension.
Under this term, it is necessary to understand the situation where the manufacturer strives to impose cheap goods in competition by "staying" the price of a competitor in order to bring a greater market share to itself and thus increase its own profits.
On a mass scale, this means for most entrepreneurs either to translate production abroad, or to buy there cheaply, or to disappear.The result is high unemployment in countries where labor prices are high compared to other economies.
Since private capital has no social responsibility and thus responsibility for its produced unemployment, the social expenditure of the state necessarily increases.
The whole situation is amplified by the complete unwillingness of the entrepreneurs to pay taxes and thus to compensate for the economic and social social damage he has done in the pursuit of profit.
The situation is so widely known that there is no need to provide specific statistical data.
Unscrupulous private capital practices create a situation in individual economies where national governments are forced to enter into mutual competition in order to artificially reduce the social level of their own population in order to attract foreign capital to the country.
In other words, governments give private capital their own populations, regardless of the social slumping.
This is mainly reflected in the changes in applicable laws.
The aim is to economically force the population to adopt the price dictate of private capital, especially in the area of wages.
This is done both by a system of economic coercion in the event of long-term unemployment and by restricting the rights of employees in the field of labour law.
The result is rising poverty, along with an increase in the gap between the poor and the rich.
Public food dispensaries for the poor have been in the Federal Republic of Germany for many years who cannot make a living from their own work.
The number of these people is already going up to the millions.
In order to increase the competitiveness of the German economy, there are quite commonly cases that properly employed people receive such wages that the state must pay them to an existential minimum.
Such a scandal was also published in the case of auxiliary employees of the Bundestag.
The economical measures of virtually all southern EU states undoubtedly lead to the same situation where people, under the pressure of a catastrophic social level, are forced to either emigrate as it was in the 19th century, or to live on the margins of society in the hope that private investment capital will come to the country one day.
But here it is necessary to ask where it will come from?
If it is from other EU countries, then poverty will move from one country to another, or it will not come at all, because the Chinese, Indian, Brazilian, or Turk, the Moroccan, or the Egyptian, or the African are still working for a fraction of the European wage.
This applies to all of Latin America.
Liberal theories and media misbehaves that the state cannot capitalize on its own economy, that a managed economy is leading to an economic catastrophe.
Private capital stubbornly insists on the opinion that the State must not interfere with the economy by directing interventions.
Then it is necessary to ask whether private capital does not affect, now it actually governs politics and thus the whole state in its own egoistic sense.
Here is the clear answer that yes.
The proof is the existence of practically the omnipotent and ubiquitous lobby in all states.
The result is a desperate situation manifested in the area of corruption, the provision of mutual benefits, legislation, where practically everything is criminal, but nothing criminal.
In Germany, the situation is such that the state ministries for lack of funds are commissioning the draft laws to private law firms that are usually in contact with industry.
These bills are then agreed in the Bundestag.
All power thus comes not in this way from the people, as Western-type constitutions preach, but from financially strong groups that prefer their own interests.
It is clear that liberal-oriented democracies are now quickly in a situation, as described by Appianos in his work of the Crisis of the Roman Republic in the time of Caesar and Pompeia: "The state has long been in complete disarray and the authorities were occupied by violence.
For bribery, illegal acquisition of favor and with the help of stones or swords.
The bribery and corruption flourished without any inhibitions, and the people went to the polls with a pre-sold vote" ..."characteric people did not apply for the office at all, so that once, as a result of this disruption, the state was without consuls for eight months." “It has indeed begun to be said that the only remedy in the evil situation is self-government, and that it is necessary to choose an energetic man.” Appiano thought of Pompeio, but he became Caesar, who turned democracy into self-government.
Conclusion As in Antiquity, the current society is based on the reckless preference of its own benefit, regardless of the social interest.
Private capital is no longer inherently able to understand and exercise society-wide benefit.
The result is now, like then, an unprecedented decadence of the elites without any effort to reform a deeper character.
The causality of the rise of both fascist and communist regimes must therefore be sought in the reckless liberalization of the economic systems of the 19th and 20 century.
In the present state, the demise of these systems in favor of liberal-type democracy can be considered a certain recess with the expectation of another round.
Especially catastrophic is the fact that the current elites are completely ignoring in the future of possible hundreds of thousands of casualties, humanitarian and social catastrophes, which we are already witnessing together with crimes against humanity as we know them from old and new history.
The abolition of the Public Works Act is not a solution, at least not permanent.
Under pressure from competition at both international and internal European level, the government of the Czech Republic will be forced to continue to look for ways to further reduce the social level of the population.
This trend is therefore systemic.
The solution is targeted political-social reforms that will strengthen the capital participation of the state in the economy, strengthen the influence of citizens on the government and weaken the monopoly position of private capital in society for the benefit of the state.
