Argo: When It's The Worst, Call Hollywood
In November 1979, a crowd of demonstrating Islamist students occupied the U.S. Embassy in Tehran and captured 52 diplomats hostage.
They were to be released in exchange for the overthrown Shah of Mohammed Reza Pahlavi, who after the revolution fled to the United States, who were the patron saint of his regime for several decades.
For the U.S. administration, the situation did not offer a positive way out - she could not afford to throw the shah overboard, because it would so fundamentally jeopardize trust in allies in other countries.
But the release of the hostages in Iran, where the revolution resulted in the establishment of theocratic regime, was unable to achieve.
It was a blow to the prestige of the United States, which was later deepened by the fiasco of the attempt to free the hostage by force.
Inmates were eventually released after 444 days, after the negotiations were brokered by the Algerian government.
Their lot at home sparked a wave of solidarity and anti-Iranian sentiment.
The debacle in Iran contributed significantly to Jimmy Carter's loss to Ronald Reagan in the 1980 presidential election.
The film directed by actor Ben Affleck Argo describes one episode of the history that brought America a small victory.
Just before the embassy was filled, six employees escaped from it.
After the complex peripeties, they ended up in the residence of the Canadian ambassador.
The CIA, in cooperation with the Canadian authorities, managed to get them out of Iran, helped by an extravagant cover story - they went to Canadian passports as members of a film crew that surveyed the locations for filming a sci-fi movie in the country.
Combination of genres
The plan, invented by "exfiltration" expert Tony Mendez, also required Hollywood's cooperation.
In order to make the legend believable, the film project was written in specialized magazines, there were press conferences, the fictional production company had a real office.
The details of the operation have been kept secret for a long time, the film is based on Tony Mendez's memories.
Affleck's film is a special combination of multiple genres.
On the one hand, a realistically conceived political thriller, at the same time the so-called "caper movie", the story of a successful piece, a betrayal - an example of Danny's team series.
The film alternates with moods - on the one hand, documentary sequences from Tehran (in the subtitle sequence are shown iconic period photographs of events and the way in which the same situations were presented in the film - there are no big differences in this).
On the other hand, lightweight passages from Hollywood, dealt with irony and mild exaggeration.
And then the scenes from the CIA headquarters and other institutions -men in suits discuss the situation at the negotiating tables, in the hallways of the office, on the phone...
Ben Affleck has managed to restart his career in a remarkable way.
From a mocked actor he became a respected director and his acting ceased to be the target of ironic remarks.
Argo is his third feature film, after the dark crime Gone Baby Gone (2007) and the thriller City (2010).
It is also the first Affleck film that doesn’t take place in the director’s home Boston.
The feeling for the atmosphere of the place was one of the characteristics that the director's older films escalated above the Hollywood standard.
And Affleck shows him in Argo, where Tehran "plays" Canada.
The best scenes in the film take place in the streets, while reconstructing real events - the opening sequence of the fall of the embassy is impressive in its clarity, which at the same time conveys the emotion of confusion and unconvincibility, which occurs when history moves somewhere out of the blue.
Affleck and his collaborators achieve a similar effect in scenes of the fictional (a fake crew at the Tehran bazaar).
Too many events in too many places
The director also had to deal with the fact that the story does not actually offer much in the cinematic sense of thrilling scenes.
He almost works with it quite successfully, sometimes he thinks of something about reality - everything does not work out so elegantly there (a scene in which the impending crisis at the Tehran airport turns the phone call in America and the chase after the runway quite far-fetched).
But the weakness of Argo is the distraction resulting from the need to show too many plots in too many places.
Alan Arkin and John Goodman are very charming in the roles of Hollywood collaborators, but their characters deserve more space and are far from the only film.
Affleck's film kind of loses a dramatic turn, it's a picture that can be watched with a slight interest, to appreciate the realization and retro style evoking thrillers of the 70's.
But it's hard to tear down.
As a reminder of one still certain way of living history and proof of how exaggerated the notions of all-powerful and omniscient secret services are, but it is sufficient.
